s threatened to privatize or shut down this seemingly obsolete and crumbling industry, but the plantation community, led by strident trade unions, has successfully resisted. Overgrown cinchona fields and shuttered quinine factories may appear the stuff of postcolonial and postindustrial ruination, but quinine's remains are not dead. Rather, they have become the site of urgent efforts to redefine land and life for the twenty-first century. Quinine's Remains offers a vivid historical and ethnographic portrait of what it means to forge life after empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCinchonaxPolitical aspectszIndiazDarjeeling (District)xHistoryy21st century. 0aQuinine industryzIndiazDarjeeling (District)xHistoryy21st century. 0aQuininexPolitical aspectszIndiazDarjeeling (District)xHistoryy21st century. 0aQuininezIndiazDarjeeling (District)xHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520399136zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520399136zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520399136/original  a978-3-11-079135-8 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA